  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Gold
  author: Kim Bu-ui
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your humble servant bears witness. On the sixteenth day of this sixth month, the Imperial Envoy and his retinue arrived bearing the royal edict and separate records. By the grace of the Imperial Majesty's tender compassion, gifts have been bestowed upon me—robes adorned with gold, silver vessels and ornaments, bolts of patterned silk, and horses. The imperial messenger has come, and heaven's light reaches far; I bow in reception of these gifts, yet my heart trembles like ice and fire at once.

    I humbly contemplate: Your Imperial Majesty embodies the virtue of Shun and advances the great enterprises of the Zhou, preserving the achievements of former ages and transmitting the vast foundations whole to posterity. In enlightened wisdom, Your Majesty shapes destiny itself, attending diligently to the affairs of first governance. Thus do you remember our eastern realm, true descendants through generations of loyal service. You have shown us the ranks of high office and the weight of your instruction, bestowing upon us abundant favor and extraordinary grace. Receiving your authority at such proximity, I am struck with awe; reading your words of heartfelt concern, I can only weep.

    Reflecting upon our remote domain, long nurtured by imperial teaching, from the days of our ancestors we have received extraordinary benevolence. In recent times we have redoubled our devotion inward. Yet suddenly the borderlands have been troubled, and our tributary visits to the capital have been delayed. Moreover, the imperial house has faced trials; the imperial court has withdrawn to distant places. My fears multiply, yet I know not the details. I have found no path to soar forth, no means to attend upon you in exile. Though I should share in bearing the empire's sorrows and wield the loyalty of righteous anger, my strength is meager and my talents slight—I cannot display the service of defending the throne. My anxieties deepen, watched by heaven itself.

    Since assuming stewardship of our realm, I have encountered calamity: successive droughts and famines have brought ruin to our people; within, rebellious ministers have risen in violence; without, powerful neighbors watch for advantage. Barely have we begun to restore order and negotiate peace with our neighbors—hardly a matter of achievement, yet we are grateful no greater troubles have erupted. Though I would wish to exhaust our nation's resources in obedience to your commands and dedicate whatever humble efforts we possess to repay generations of imperial favor, circumstances constrain us and events resist easy resolution. I can only hope that your sage wisdom will look with mercy upon my sincerity, recognizing that I stand amid hardship not through willful negligence but through genuine constraint. If you would extend your forbearance and allow us to endure whole, then shall the standards of righteousness remain intact, and we shall not fail in our duty as a small state serving a great one. Where your virtue and authority reach, how could we forget our reverence for the throne? I swear by the sun itself and pray that heaven observes my oath.

    I am overwhelmed with gratitude for heaven's favor and the sage's virtue, my emotions too intense to contain. The edicts and proclamations shall be addressed in subsequent memorial through my subordinates. This letter of thanks is now sent with the departing envoy as our formal response.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This is a formal memorial (봉사문) sent by the ruler of a tributary state in response to gifts and recognition from the Chinese imperial court, likely during a period when the Korean kingdom faced internal or external difficulties that prevented regular tribute missions.
  - key: ''
    value: The references to 'ice and fire' (氷炭) reflect the traditional Korean poetic convention of expressing conflicting emotions of gratitude and anxiety in the presence of imperial authority.
  - key: ''
    value: The mention of 'rebellious ministers' and border troubles suggests this was written during a period of internal unrest in Korea, possibly the mid-15th century.
  - key: ''
    value: '''Shun'' and ''Zhou'' are references to legendary Chinese sage-kings and dynasties, used here as metaphors for virtuous imperial governance.'
